🏗 Section 6: Adaptive Refinements & Debt Management

Role & Purpose in the Manual
	•	This section is the governance framework for the “costs of delivery trade-offs.” It handles things that are neither pure scope change nor pure defect but are refinements, shortcuts, or structural inefficiencies that accrue risk over time.
	•	It gives the Delivery Team a disciplined way to track, fund, repay, and govern various kinds of debt — so that they don’t become invisible monsters in later phases.
	•	It also teaches how to continue evolving while protecting stability — interpreting rework and debt as manageable artifacts, not failures.

⸻

🎯 Promise: What This Section Will Deliver

By the end of Section 6, the reader will:
	•	Understand the difference between adaptive refinements (learning-driven rework) and debt (intentional trade-offs).
	•	Know how to classify different forms of debt: technical, solution, process, expediency.
	•	Be able to maintain a Debt Portfolio (register, catch-up plan, funding source, status).
	•	Understand how, when, and who should pay debt repayment (origin-based responsibility).
	•	Use Catch-Up Plans (milestones, phased repayment) rather than single paybacks.
	•	Be able to integrate debt metrics and dashboards into governance (alerts, dashboards, residual risk).
	•	Know how to review debt items in Steering / Governance forums and prioritize repayment vs new features.

In short: you’ll gain a structured mechanism to let your program evolve but under guardrails — no runaway debt.

