⚙️ Guidance to the Reader: VP Coaching on Debt Strategy
	1.	Name & Document All Trade-offs Immediately
	•	Whenever you skip a test, postpone a refactor, or defer an architectural decision, call it Expediency Debt or Process Debt. Don’t let it vanish.
	•	Always record rationale, owner, and intended repayment plan.
	2.	Use Catch-Up Plans, Not “One-Shot Paybacks”
	•	Break repayment into incremental goals (e.g. 20% every quarter).
	•	Tie repayment tasks to upcoming feature sprints, so debt doesn’t become “extra” work.
	3.	Prioritize Debt Items by Risk, Not Order of Discovery
	•	High residual risk or interdependency => repay first.
	•	Use metrics like how often the debt area is touched or how many defects attached.
	4.	Balance Feature vs Debt Work
	•	Don’t let debt repayment starve feature delivery — reserve a stable capacity chunk.
	•	Use guardrails (e.g. 10–20% of sprint capacity) to pay down debt gradually.
	5.	Treat Debt as Visible, Not Hidden
	•	Display debt portfolio metrics in dashboards.
	•	Escalate large debt that exceeds thresholds.
	•	Use debt visibility as a signal for budget or re-baseline conversations.
	6.	Align Debt Review with Steering & Governance
	•	At each Steering cycle, show debt trends, repayment progress, and proposed adjustments.
	•	Use decision forums to decide which debt to accelerate or delay.
	7.	Prevent New Debt from Outpacing Repayment
	•	Monitor debt accumulation rate vs debt paydown rate.
	•	Block or slow new debt if accumulation outpaces repayment.

From the Field: “We had 15% expediency debt accumulated in three sprints. Because we never documented it, by month six we were doing more debt work than new features — the backlog reversed itself.”

VP Reflection: “Debt is like interest — small if paid, crippling if ignored. The difference between “fast now” and “slow later” is how early you govern it.”

